With this approach, the type of the value field returned on iterator next becomes the current value type, right? I don't think that is correct. The next value ideally shouldn't change between next invocations of the same iterator.
public function main() {
    'xml:Text x1 = xml `foo`;
    xml<'xml:Element|'xml:Text> x2 = <xml<'xml:Element|'xml:Text>> x1.concat(xml `<bar/>`);

    var iterator = x2.iterator();
    record {| 'xml:Element|'xml:Text value; |}? next = iterator.next();

    boolean b1 = <any> next is record {| 'xml:Element|'xml:Text value; |}; // true
    boolean b2 = next is record {| 'xml:Element value; |}; // false
    boolean b3 = next is record {| 'xml:Text value; |}; // true - should be false!

    record {| 'xml:Element|'xml:Text value; |}? nextNext = iterator.next();

    boolean b4 = <any> nextNext is record {| 'xml:Element|'xml:Text value; |}; // true
    boolean b5 = nextNext is record {| 'xml:Element value; |}; // true - should be false!
    boolean b6 = nextNext is record {| 'xml:Text value; |}; // false
}

